### C7. `providedIn: 'root'` on `HotelStateService` — singleton leak risk

**File**: [hotel-state.service.ts](file:///home/nurlansarkhanov/Desktop/code/Revelton/thingsboard-extention/src/app/components/revelton-tb-extension-dashboard/core/services/hotel-state.service.ts#L156)

```typescript
@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class HotelStateService implements OnDestroy { ... }
```

As a root singleton, this service persists for the entire app lifecycle. If a user navigates away and back:
- The `discoveryDone = true` flag prevents re-discovery
- `roomMap`, `discoveredDevices`, `ctxOtherDevices` retain stale data
- `refreshTimer` keeps firing with a potentially stale `ctx`

In ThingsBoard widget context, this is especially dangerous because `ctx.http` may become invalid when the widget is destroyed.

> [!WARNING]
> **Fix**: Either scope the service to the dashboard component module, or implement proper reset/cleanup when the widget context changes.

---

### C8. No unit tests anywhere

There are **zero test files** in the entire codebase. For a system that controls physical HVAC equipment (thermostats), this is a serious risk. A bug in `saveAttribute()` could set all thermostats to maximum temperature.

> [!CAUTION]
> **Fix**: At minimum, write tests for:
> - `RoomDataService.calculateAirQuality()` — pure function, easy to test
> - `RoomDataService.updateFromTelemetry()` — core data pipeline
> - `extractRoomNumber()` — regex parsing, edge cases matter
> - `saveAttribute()` — validates bounds before RPC
> - `calcStatus()` — threshold logic

---

## 🟡 MAJOR Issues (Should fix before production)

### M1. Massive `any` type usage (100+ occurrences)

**Files**: Across the entire codebase, particularly [room-data.service.ts](file:///home/nurlansarkhanov/Desktop/code/Revelton/thingsboard-extention/src/app/components/revelton-tb-extension-dashboard/core/services/room-data.service.ts#L66-L94)

The `RoomData` interface has **18 `any`-typed fields**:
```typescript
windowDevices: any;
trvDevices: any;
tempDevices: any;
// ... 15 more
```

Additionally, `ctx: any` is passed everywhere with no typing. This defeats TypeScript's purpose and makes refactoring dangerous.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Fix**: Replace with proper types:
> ```typescript
> windowDevices: Record<string, { contact: 'open' | 'closed' }>;
> trvDevices: Record<string, TrvDeviceData>;
> tempDevices: Record<string, number>;
> ```

---

### M2. Unsubscribed HTTP observables in discovery pipeline

**File**: [hotel-state.service.ts](file:///home/nurlansarkhanov/Desktop/code/Revelton/thingsboard-extention/src/app/components/revelton-tb-extension-dashboard/core/services/hotel-state.service.ts#L361-L377)

```typescript
this.httpGetWithRetry(ctx, `/api/device/info/${entityId}`, 1)
  .then((deviceInfo: any) => { ... })
  .catch(() => {
    this.httpGetWithRetry(ctx, `/api/device/${entityId}`, 1)
      .then(...)
      .catch(() => {}); // ← silently swallowed
  });
```

Fire-and-forget HTTP calls during datasource scanning. For a hotel with 20 rooms × 5 devices = 100 device profile lookups **per data update cycle**. These calls are not tracked, not cancellable, and not debounced.

---

### M3. `console.log` in production data path

**File**: [hotel-state.service.ts](file:///home/nurlansarkhanov/Desktop/code/Revelton/thingsboard-extention/src/app/components/revelton-tb-extension-dashboard/core/services/hotel-state.service.ts#L487)

```typescript
console.log(`[Mews] key="${item.dataKey?.name}" val="${val}" → status=${stats.mewsStatus} ...`);
```

This is an unconditional `console.log` (not behind the `DEBUG` flag) that fires on every Mews telemetry update. Also [room-data.service.ts:1004-1018](file:///home/nurlansarkhanov/Desktop/code/Revelton/thingsboard-extention/src/app/components/revelton-tb-extension-dashboard/core/services/room-data.service.ts#L1004-L1018) has unconditional room status logging.

---

### M4. `toPromise()` is deprecated in RxJS 7+

**File**: [room-detail-panel.component.ts](file:///home/nurlansarkhanov/Desktop/code/Revelton/thingsboard-extention/src/app/components/revelton-tb-extension-dashboard/features/room-view/room-detail-panel.component.ts#L1530)

```typescript
return http.get(`...`).toPromise().catch(() => null);
```

`toPromise()` was deprecated in RxJS 7 and may be removed in future versions. Use `firstValueFrom()` or `lastValueFrom()` instead.

---

### M5. Escaped regex in `formatDeviceName` — will never match

**File**: [hotel-state.service.ts](file:///home/nurlansarkhanov/Desktop/code/Revelton/thingsboard-extention/src/app/components/revelton-tb-extension-dashboard/core/services/hotel-state.service.ts#L961)

```typescript
const fullMatch = name.match(/^([a-zA-Z]+)_room_(\\d+)_(\\d+)$/i);
```

The double-escaped `\\d` will look for a literal `\d` in the string, not a digit. This means the `formatDeviceName` method in `HotelStateService` **never matches** any device name pattern. The function always falls through to `return name;`.

> [!WARNING]
> **Fix**: Use single backslash: `/^([a-zA-Z]+)_room_(\d+)_(\d+)$/i`

---

### M6. Multiple competing refresh timers

The codebase has **4 separate `setInterval` refresh cycles** running simultaneously:

| Timer | Location | Interval | Purpose |
|-------|----------|----------|---------|
| `refreshTimer` | HotelStateService | 30s | Re-fetch all device telemetry |
| `refreshInterval` | ReveltonDashboardComponent | 10s | Periodic UI refresh + dialog sync |
| `refreshInterval` | RoomDetailPanelComponent | 10s | Rebuild + re-fetch historical vitals |
| `timeInterval` | ReveltonDashboardComponent | 60s | Clock update |

The first three all trigger HTTP calls. Combined with ThingsBoard's own WebSocket subscription pushing data, this creates a thundering herd problem:
- Every 10s: UI rebuilds + historical vitals fetch
- Every 30s: Full device telemetry refresh (100+ HTTP calls)
- Continuous: TB WebSocket pushes trigger `onDataUpdated()`

---

### M7. Fragile device identification via entity name regex

**File**: [room-data.service.ts](file:///home/nurlansarkhanov/Desktop/code/Revelton/thingsboard-extention/src/app/components/revelton-tb-extension-dashboard/core/services/room-data.service.ts#L823-L882)

Device type detection relies on string matching against entity names:
```typescript
return n.startsWith('AQ') || n.startsWith('AIR') || n.startsWith('AM') || 
       n.includes('AM308') || n.includes('MILESIGHT') || ...
```

If a device is named differently (e.g., renamed by hotel staff in ThingsBoard), it silently falls through to the wrong category. The occupancy sensor detection at [line 867](file:///home/nurlansarkhanov/Desktop/code/Revelton/thingsboard-extention/src/app/components/revelton-tb-extension-dashboard/core/services/room-data.service.ts#L867) matches `n.includes('370')` which could match room 370.

---

### M8. `Object.assign` mutation on dialog data

**File**: [revelton-hotel.component.ts](file:///home/nurlansarkhanov/Desktop/code/Revelton/thingsboard-extention/src/app/components/revelton-tb-extension-dashboard/features/hotel-dashboard/revelton-hotel.component.ts#L414-L416)

```typescript
Object.assign(room.activeDialogRef.componentInstance.data, room.roomData);
```

This mutates the dialog component's data in-place, bypassing Angular's change detection. Combined with the `OnPush` strategy (if used), this can cause stale UI.

---

### M9. `@Input() data: any` — the entire room detail panel is untyped

**File**: [room-detail-panel.component.ts](file:///home/nurlansarkhanov/Desktop/code/Revelton/thingsboard-extention/src/app/components/revelton-tb-extension-dashboard/features/room-view/room-detail-panel.component.ts#L24)

```typescript
@Input() data: any;
```

This is the primary data input for a 1,607-line component. Every property access is unchecked (`this.data.trvDevices`, `this.data.ctx`, `this.data.windowDevices`). A single missing field causes a silent `undefined` propagation.

---

### M10. `localStorage` as alert persistence layer

**File**: [room-detail-panel.component.ts](file:///home/nurlansarkhanov/Desktop/code/Revelton/thingsboard-extention/src/app/components/revelton-tb-extension-dashboard/features/room-view/room-detail-panel.component.ts#L1403-L1454)

Alert acknowledgements and history are stored in `localStorage`. This means:
- Data is lost if the user clears browser data or uses a different browser
- No cross-device sync (mobile staff won't see acknowledged alerts)
- `localStorage` has a ~5MB limit; with 50 alerts × many rooms, this grows
- For a **hotel operations dashboard**, alert state should be server-side

---

### M11. Duplicate code: `extractRoomNumber` and `formatDeviceName`

The `extractRoomNumber` method exists identically in `HotelStateService` (with comment "1:1 copy from revelton-hotel.component.ts"). `formatDeviceName` is duplicated between `HotelStateService` and `RoomDetailPanelComponent` with slightly different implementations.

---

### M12. `fetchHistoricalVitals` fires on every `updateData()` call

**File**: [room-detail-panel.component.ts](file:///home/nurlansarkhanov/Desktop/code/Revelton/thingsboard-extention/src/app/components/revelton-tb-extension-dashboard/features/room-view/room-detail-panel.component.ts#L456-L463)

```typescript
public updateData(): void {
  this.buildFromPassedData();
  this.fetchHistoricalVitals(); // ← HTTP call every 10 seconds
  // ...
}
```

`updateData()` is called every 10 seconds by the `refreshInterval`. `fetchHistoricalVitals` has a cache key check, but the key only changes on room or time range change — however, it still enters the function, creates promises, and checks conditions on every cycle.

---

### M13. No error boundary in the data processing pipeline

If `RoomDataService.updateFromTelemetry()` throws for one room, the entire `_doProcessDataUpdate` loop aborts, and no other rooms get updated. There's a top-level try/catch in the debounce subscriber, but it catches the error and logs — leaving all rooms stale.

---

### M14. `settings-panel/` directory exists but is empty

Listed in the architecture docs as "reserved for future use." Empty directories in production builds are noise and signal incomplete work.

---

## 🟢 Strengths — What's Done Well

1. **Solid architectural separation**: `core/services`, `features/`, `shared/components` — clean layer boundaries
2. **Debounced data processing**: `PROCESS_DEBOUNCE_MS = 300` prevents rapid TB `onDataUpdated` from flooding the pipeline
3. **HTTP retry with timeout**: `httpGetWithRetry` is well-implemented with exponential backoff
4. **Optimistic UI with lock mechanism**: Thermostat controls use `modeLockUntil`/`presetLockUntil` to prevent UI flicker during RPC roundtrip
5. **Configurable thresholds**: Air quality, noise, temperature thresholds are driven by `ControlPanelService` config
6. **AQI calculation**: EPA breakpoint-based linear interpolation is scientifically sound
7. **Multi-language support**: EN/RU translation system with reactive `BehaviorSubject`
8. **Theme system**: CSS variable injection with multiple palettes (light/dark per theme)
9. **Smart device classification**: Falls back through multiple strategies (profile name → entity name → regex)
10. **Reservation state machine**: Mews integration covers all states (started, confirmed, optional, processed, canceled) with proper edge cases (overdue, late arrival)

---

## 📋 Prioritized Fix Plan

### Phase 1: "Stop the Bleeding" (1–2 days)
- [ ] **C1**: Set `DEBUG = false`
- [ ] **C2**: Remove or flag mock guest count
- [ ] **C3**: Remove test devices from `other-devices-panel`
- [ ] **M3**: Remove/guard unconditional `console.log` statements
- [ ] **M5**: Fix escaped regex in `formatDeviceName`

### Phase 2: "Safety Guards" (3–5 days)
- [ ] **C4**: Add input validation on RPC commands (temperature bounds, mode whitelist)
- [ ] **C5+C6**: Extract hardcoded timezone/coordinates to a config constant
- [ ] **M6**: Consolidate refresh timers to a single orchestrated refresh cycle
- [ ] **M4**: Replace `toPromise()` with `firstValueFrom()`
- [ ] **M13**: Add per-room try/catch in the processing loop

### Phase 3: "Type Safety & Reliability" (1–2 weeks)
- [ ] **M1**: Replace `any` types with proper interfaces (start with `RoomData`)
- [ ] **M9**: Type the `@Input() data` in `RoomDetailPanelComponent`
- [ ] **M7**: Add device profile-based identification alongside name-based fallback
- [ ] **C7**: Scope `HotelStateService` to dashboard module or add proper reset
- [ ] **M11**: Extract shared utilities to prevent code duplication

### Phase 4: "Production Grade" (2–3 weeks)
- [ ] **C8**: Write tests for core services and critical paths
- [ ] **M10**: Move alert persistence to server-side (ThingsBoard attributes or custom DB)
- [ ] **M2**: Track and cancel in-flight HTTP calls during discovery
- [ ] **M14**: Remove empty `settings-panel/` or implement it
- [ ] Add proper error boundaries and user-facing error states
- [ ] Add performance monitoring (track refresh cycle duration)

---

## IoT-Specific Recommendations

| Concern | Current State | Recommendation |
|---------|--------------|----------------|
| Device offline detection | 24h stale threshold | Add configurable timeout per device profile (TRV: 30min, LoRaWAN: 2h) |
| Command confirmation | Fire-and-forget RPC | Implement read-back verification: set temp → wait 5s → read back → confirm |
| Batch operations | One-at-a-time | Add "Set all TRVs to eco mode" batch command |
| Data export | Not available | Add CSV/PDF export for historical data (hotel compliance) |
| Audit trail | Client-side only | Log all RPC commands server-side with user ID, timestamp, old/new value |
| Connectivity | No detection | Add visual indicator when TB WebSocket disconnects |
| Stale data | No visual cue | Add "Last updated X seconds ago" badge per room card |

---

> [!NOTE]
> This audit covers code quality and production-readiness. A separate **security audit** covering authentication flows, API endpoint authorization, and cross-site scripting (XSS) in template bindings is recommended before public deployment.
